<DOC><DOCNO> AP880801-0237 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0739EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Pullman     08-01 0319</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Pullman,0332</SECOND><HEAD>Pullman Accepts $650 Million Buyout By Forstmann Little</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The investment firm Forstmann Little andamp; Co. istaking Pullman Co. private in a buyout it values at about $650million, having convinced the company to drop a management-ledbuyout plan.   Forstmann Little, which specializes in leveraged buyouts,announced Sunday Pullman had agreed to a buyout at $9.25 cash pershare for its 41.9 million outstanding shares, or about $387.57million.   Assumption of existing debt and expenses will make the totalprice of the buyout about $650 million, Forstmann Little stated.   The buyout was conditioned on Pullman terminating its earlieragreement for a $7.75 per share buyout by a group led by Thomas M.Begel, the company's chairman and chief executive, and HenleyManufacturing Corp., Pullman's biggest shareholder with 9 percentof the company's outstanding shares.   Pullman stock closed unchanged at $9 a share Friday on the NewYork Stock Exchange.   ``I am pleased that Pullman's stockholders will get the benefitof the $9.25 transaction price and am confident that by being oneof the Forstmann Little group of companies, new opportunities willbe provided for Pullman's employees,'' Begel said in a news release.   Pullman, based in Princeton, N.J., is a diversified manufacturerof industrial and engineered component products, including trucktrailers, aircraft seating, food service equipment, weapons systemscomponents, refuse disposal equipment and fluid handling systems.   ``The acquisition of Pullman is an opportunity for ForstmannLittle to purchase a well-managed diverse group of industrialbusinesses, which have strong niche market positions,'' saidNicholas C. Forstmann, a general partner of Forstmann Little.   In a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired mainly withborrowed funds that are repaid with money raised by the targetcompany's cash flow or the sale of its assets.   The Begel group had planned to sell a number of Pullman'sbusinesses and divisions to pay off debt incurred in its buyout.</TEXT></DOC>